SIMPLE: tumult
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tumult
<hw>Tu"mult</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>tumultus</ets>; probably akin to Skr. <ets>tumula</ets> noise,
noisy, and perhaps to L. <ets>tumere</ets> to swell, E.
<ets>tumid</ets>: cf. F. <ets>tumulte</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
commotion or agitation of a multitude, usually accompanied with great
noise, uproar, and confusion of voices; hurly-burly; noisy
confusion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What meaneth the noise of this <qex>tumult</qex> ?</q> <rj><qau>1
Sam. iv. 14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Till in loud <qex>tumult</qex> all the Greeks arose.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Violent commotion or agitation, with confusion of
sounds; <as>as, the <ex>tumult</ex> of the elements</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Irregular or confused motion; agitation; high
excitement; <as>as, the <ex>tumult</ex> of the spirits or
passions</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Uproar; ferment; disturbance; turbulence;
disorder; confusion; noise; bluster; hubbub; bustle; stir; brawl;
riot.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tumult</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tumult
<hw>Tu"mult</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To make a tumult;
to be in great commotion.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Importuning and <qex>tumulting</qex> even to the fear of a
revolt.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tumulter</ent>⟦br⟧
